#Text=ELECTION INTELLIGENCE.
#Text=Dublin University.
#Text=—We have authority for stating that Mr.
#Text=H.
#Text=E.
#Text=Chatterton, will present himself to the electors of the University of Dublin, in tbe event of a vacancy occurring.
#Text=There are now four candidates in the field—Mr.
#Text=J.
#Text=E.
#Text=Walsh, Q.C.; Sir Elward Grogan, Mr.
#Text=Chatterton, and Mr.
#Text=R.
#Text=Longtield.— Lublin Evening MaiU Corrupt Practices at Elections.
#Text=—A return has been issued from which it appears that ten royal commissioners have been appointed to investigate the conupt practices at elections since 1852.
#Text=Six of these were appointed in 1853, one in 1857, and three in 1859.

#Text=The total expenses have amounted to £21,466 6s. 5d., of which £12,111 19s. 7d. are appropriated to general expenses, £3,463 6s. 3d. to shorthand-writing, and £5,891 os. 7d. to printing and stationery.
#Text=Eight prosecutions were ordered at an expense of £4,952 3s. 4d., but as in each a case a nolle prosequi was entered, the prosecutions have, of course, meant nothing.
#Text=The Helston Election Committee.
#Text=—The Helston election committee, which meets to-day, must of necessity last a considerable time.
#Text=After disposing of the first question, namely, whether the mayors casting vote, which decided ihe election, was properly received or no, the scrutiny v ill be proceeded with.
#Text=Twenty of the votes recorded for the fitting member (Mr.
#Text=Campbell) are disputed by the petitioners, whilst eighty of the votes recorded for Mr.
#Text=Baliol Brett, the unsuccessful candidate at the last election and one of the petitioners against the return of Mr.
#Text=Campbell, are disputed by the agents for that gentleman. __
